  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Valero generated <strong>$5.03 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, representing the true cash-generating power of its refineries.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We model FCF growth at <strong>3% per year</strong> for 5 years. Valero operates in a highly cyclical and mature industry (refining). While recent years saw massive spikes in crack spreads, returning to a normalized, steady low-growth environment is the most prudent assumption for a long-term model.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2% forever</strong> — roughly keeping pace with inflation. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate). This captures all value from Year 6 to infinity.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>10%</strong> — our required rate of return. This is the cost of equity for a large-cap energy company with a low beta (0.73). It's significantly above the 10Y Treasury (4.18%) plus a reasonable equity risk premium, providing a buffer for commodity cycle risk.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$7.0B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding (299M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">3%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Refining is notoriously cyclical. Valero enjoyed record FCF during 2022-2023, but numbers have since normalized. Instead of projecting explosive growth or a harsh contraction, we project a 3% steady growth rate from a conservative FY2025 base, assuming steady operational efficiency and share repurchases supporting per-share value.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">10%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Equity risk premium: ~5.5%. Beta: 0.73. CAPM gives ~8.2%. We round up to 10% — adding a margin of safety for the inherent volatility and regulatory risks of the refining sector. We demand a robust 10% annual return to hold this asset.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is ~3%, and inflation targets are ~2%. As the world transitions toward renewable energy over the coming decades, a terminal growth rate of 2% is a highly realistic, arguably generous assumption for fossil-fuel refining cash flows in perpetuity.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

