  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Crack spread expansions:</strong> If global refining capacity tightens due to geopolitics or refinery closures, refining margins could spike again, leading to temporary but massive FCF windfalls.</li>
    <li><strong>Renewable Diesel:</strong> Valero is a massive producer of renewable diesel (Diamond Green Diesel). Higher margins or expansion in this sector could offset traditional fossil fuel declines faster than expected.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Buybacks:</strong> Valero frequently buys back a significant amount of its own stock. Aggressive reductions in share count can rapidly increase intrinsic value per share.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Energy Transition:</strong> EV adoption and a shift away from fossil fuels could permanently impair gasoline and diesel demand, making our 2% terminal growth rate wildly optimistic.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Increased carbon taxes, environmental regulations, or bans on internal combustion engines would drastically increase compliance costs and reduce FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Commodity Cycle Bust:</strong> If global supply outpaces demand, crack spreads could compress significantly, leading to quarters of negative FCF.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. During commodity booms, P/E ratios look artificially low because earnings are cyclically high. A DCF forces you to smooth out cyclicality and state explicit assumptions about normalized cash flows over the long term.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 10% discount rate and not 8% or 12%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. The historical equity risk premium is ~5.5%. For a company with Valero's beta (0.73), CAPM gives ~8.2%. We use 10% — adding a margin of safety for the volatile nature of commodity refining.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why only 3% FCF growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Refining is a mature, capital-intensive industry. Valero is not a tech stock; its growth is constrained by physical throughput and crack spreads. 3% represents steady operational optimization and modest capacity expansions, avoiding the trap of projecting peak-cycle margins into perpetuity.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

